{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BaNKE5SoVyeeMRAAbHwCSc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The pod is not becoming ready. Let me try a different approach. The TLS handshake is timing out. This suggests that maybe the new cert generated has some issue that CockroachDB doesn't like, or there's something about the cert format.\n\nLet me look at what the existing working certs look like vs the new ones. The existing certs from the toolbox (before my changes) at `/tmp/certs/node.crt` were working fine. The `crdb-certs` secret's old `node.crt` was working for crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2.\n\nWait, but I already updated the `crdb-certs` secret with the new certs. \n\nActually, the Kubernetes projected volume might not have refreshed yet in the running pods. So crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 could still be serving the old certs, and when crdb-cluster-0 tries to connect with the new CA validation, the handshake fails. But that doesn't make sense either—the CA hasn't changed, so both old and new certs should validate against it.\n\nLet me trace through what's happening: crdb-cluster-0 is starting up and needs to establish connections to the other nodes.  The timeout suggests a network or connectivity issue rather than a certificate validation error. I should check if CockroachDB has specific cert format requirements that might be causing the problem.\n\nLet me verify that the CA certificate I used to sign the new node cert matches the one in the `crdb-certs` secret—if they're different CAs, nodes 1 and 2 would reject node 0's certificate even though it's properly signed. I'll compare the CA fingerprints to confirm they're the same.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":285,"cache_read_input_tokens":48244,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":285},"output_t