{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VoGex4v4xtMB7Q484DRCrp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The critical error is:\n\n```\ntls: failed to verify certificate: x509: certificate signed by unknown authority\n```\n\nNode 0 (crdb-cluster-0) is trying to connect to nodes 1 and 2, but nodes 1 and 2 are presenting certs that are \"signed by unknown authority\" from node 0's perspective.\n\nThis means: Node 0 has the new CA cert (from the updated secret), but nodes 1 and 2 are still presenting certs signed by a DIFFERENT CA than the one node 0 has loaded.\n\nWait, but I verified that the CA cert in the toolbox and the CA cert in the updated `crdb-certs` secret have the same fingerprint. So the CA should be the same.\nAh, I think I see the issue now. Nodes 1 and 2 are still running with their old secret volumes because Kubernetes projected volumes update with a delay—usually 1-2 minutes but sometimes longer. So either nodes 1 and 2 had different CAs in their original secrets, or the volume projection update simply hasn't propagated to them yet. The error is from node 0's perspective when it tries to verify the certs that nodes 1 and 2 are presenting against node 0's newly updated CA.\n\nThe real question is whether the old node certs that nodes 1 and 2 are still using were signed by the same CA as the toolbox's updated CA cert. Since I've already overwritten the `crdb-certs` secret, I can't directly see what the original CA was, but I might be able to check the CA cert that's still cached on the nodes themselves.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4175,"cache_read_input_tokens":52935,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4175},"output_tokens":37,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_