{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01W9wiVXXzsGQ6iWEsccMofz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `..data` directory was updated at 08:17 (when I patched the secret), but the symlinks were created at 08:13 (when the pod started). Wait, this is weird. In Kubernetes, when a secret is updated, the projected volume is also updated - the `..data` symlink points to the new data directory. So the symlinks at 08:13 point to `..data` which itself points to the new data directory `..2026_07_03_08_17_18.2598730840`. This means the certs on disk ARE the new ones.\nBut here's the issue: CockroachDB loaded the old certs into memory when it started at 08:13, and it doesn't automatically reload them from disk. So nodes 1 and 2 are still using the old certs in memory even though the disk has been updated. Node 0 restarted at 08:17 and loaded the new certs, but when it tries to connect to the other nodes, it gets their old node certificates from memory while presenting its new CA cert - that's the mismatch.\n\nNow I'm trying to figure out whether the original CA cert in the crdb-certs secret was even the same as the toolbox CA to begin with. I need to trace back what the original CA fingerprint was before I patched it. 't have been signed by the same CA that node 0 now has. So the original `crdb-certs` secret likely contained a CA cert that's different from the toolbox's CA, which explains why node 0 can't verify the old node certs that nodes 1 and 2 are still using in memory.\n\nThe fix is to restart all three pods at once so they load the updated certs from the secrets simultaneously, avoiding the split-brain situation where some nodes have the new CA and others don't.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1270,"cache_read_input_tokens":57110,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_